Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction The mathematical study of different spaces and manifolds has shown that these entities have interesting visual properties. Recently software has been written that allows a user to visualize different spaces and manifolds <ref> [LMP93] </ref>. However, this software only provides a small window into these fantastic spaces. To obtain a more interesting and helpful window into these worlds, we turn to a Virtual Environment (VE) system. <p> The tracking system tracks 360 ffi in yaw and 45 ffi in pitch and roll. The helmet is shown in Figure 10. 3.2 Software Base The display engine of the three-manifold virtual environment is a modified version of Geomview <ref> [LMP93] </ref>, a mathematics visualization program written and distributed by the Geometry Center, a National Science and Technology Research Center. Geomview supports viewing in all three spaces discussed | euclidean, spherical, and hyperbolic. Geomview runs on Silicon Graphics, 10 NeXT, and plain X11 workstations.
